So the engine is something
that goes through a cycle.

01:19:20.850 --> 01:19:24.920
As part of that cycle,
it does some work.

01:19:24.920 --> 01:19:27.460
But what this
expression has to do

01:19:27.460 --> 01:19:31.030
is the heat that
goes into the system.

01:19:31.030 --> 01:19:34.770
So I can regard minus
QC as the heat that

01:19:34.770 --> 01:19:40.220
goes into the engine coming from
a reservoir of temperature TC,

01:19:40.220 --> 01:19:42.290
QH going through
the engine, coming

01:19:42.290 --> 01:19:46.530
from a reservoir
of temperature TH.

01:19:46.530 --> 01:19:49.500
And you have a
relation such as this

01:19:49.500 --> 01:19:53.310
because the efficiency
of any type of engine

01:19:53.310 --> 01:19:57.240
has to be less than this
efficiency of the Carnot engine

01:19:57.240 --> 01:20:01.090
that is stamped by the
corresponding temperatures.

01:20:01.090 --> 01:20:03.900
OK, now this is kind of limited.

01:20:03.900 --> 01:20:08.550
And in order to be able to
construct a general formula,

01:20:08.550 --> 01:20:12.140
we need to be able
to make statements

01:20:12.140 --> 01:20:16.640
that's are relevant to
arbitrary complex cycles

01:20:16.640 --> 01:20:20.440
and complex behaviors.

01:20:20.440 --> 01:20:25.960
So what we will
start next time is

01:20:25.960 --> 01:20:29.110
to prove something
that ultimately

01:20:29.110 --> 01:20:31.880
will allow us to
quantify entropy.

01:20:31.880 --> 01:20:38.650
It's called Clausius'
Theorem, which

01:20:38.650 --> 01:20:44.310
states the following-- imagine
some kind of a generalization

01:20:44.310 --> 01:20:49.845
of your engine that takes place
in some multidimensional space.

01:20:49.845 --> 01:20:53.220
So rather than really
thinking about an engine,

01:20:53.220 --> 01:20:56.730
I want to think
about some substance.

01:20:56.730 --> 01:21:00.630
This was an ideal gas run
through some nice cycle.

01:21:00.630 --> 01:21:03.250
But I want to think
about some substance that

01:21:03.250 --> 01:21:07.140
is described by multiple
coordinate system.

01:21:07.140 --> 01:21:11.768
I take the system
from some point A,

01:21:11.768 --> 01:21:15.440
and the only requirement
that I place on it

01:21:15.440 --> 01:21:18.590
is that ultimately,
I do something,

01:21:18.590 --> 01:21:23.070
and I come back to
A. So it is a cycle.

01:21:23.070 --> 01:21:26.340
What I don't even
require is that this

01:21:26.340 --> 01:21:31.590
is a quasistatic process, so
that the intermediate stages

01:21:31.590 --> 01:21:35.820
are well-defined in
this coordinate space--

01:21:35.820 --> 01:21:42.560
OK, so for any arbitrary
cyclic transformation.

01:21:42.560 --> 01:21:47.110
OK, now this
transformation-- we'll do

01:21:47.110 --> 01:21:51.770
is that at various stages--
just like that simple example--

01:21:51.770 --> 01:21:53.500
we'll do work on
the environment,

01:21:53.500 --> 01:21:55.370
take work from the environment.

01:21:55.370 --> 01:21:58.330
But most importantly
from our perspective,

01:21:58.330 --> 01:22:03.300
there will be heat
input into the system

01:22:03.300 --> 01:22:07.290
at various stages of the cycle.

01:22:07.290 --> 01:22:11.410
And I'm going to look at it
from the perspective of what

01:22:11.410 --> 01:22:14.850
goes into the system,
just like in this engine.

01:22:14.850 --> 01:22:18.320
So sometimes maybe this
dQ is negative-- means

01:22:18.320 --> 01:22:21.250
that the system is
really releasing heat,

01:22:21.250 --> 01:22:25.360
just like this engine
was releasing the heat.

01:22:25.360 --> 01:22:29.690
Now, Clausius' Theorem
says that if you integrate

01:22:29.690 --> 01:22:34.120
all around the cycle,
these elements of heat

01:22:34.120 --> 01:22:39.430
that you input to the system
throughout various stages

01:22:39.430 --> 01:22:44.980
of the cyclic transformation,
and divide them by some T.

01:22:44.980 --> 01:22:51.300
And this is kind of something
that needs definition.

01:22:51.300 --> 01:22:54.200
And S is supposed to
parametrize the cycle.

01:22:54.200 --> 01:22:58.580
Let's say S goes from 0 to 1
as you go across the cycle.

01:22:58.580 --> 01:23:00.790
Generalizing that is negative.

01:23:04.330 --> 01:23:08.090
Next time, we will see if this
system is non-equilibrium,

01:23:08.090 --> 01:23:11.850
what exactly I mean
by this T of S.

01:23:11.850 --> 01:23:16.690
And we will see, somehow,
that once I define this,

01:23:16.690 --> 01:23:19.470
by doing part of
this, I can actually

01:23:19.470 --> 01:23:24.610
define an entropy function
integral from A to B dQ over S,

01:23:24.610 --> 01:23:30.020
and complete the definition of
what needs to be put for the Q

01:23:30.020 --> 01:23:36.450
in order to give you an
expression for T. OK.

